) - Reviews - GospelFlava.com|work=GospelFlava.com|first=Stan |last=North |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><br><small>([[Jacky Clark-Chisholm]] featuring the Clark Sisters)</small>\n| 2005\n| ''[[Expectancy]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Higher Ground\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2009/aprilweb-only/ohhappyday-mini.html|title=Oh Happy Day: An All-Star Music Celebration|work=[[Christianity Today]]|date=April 7, 2009|first=Andrew |last=Greer |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><br><small>([[Robert Randolph]] & the Clark Sisters)</small>\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2009\n| ''[[Oh Happy Day: An All-Star Music Celebration]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"I Wanna Thank You\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/1RJcTyUVMHQD1VRMas8u8r|title=\t\nSilky Soul Music... an All-star Tribute to Maze featuring Frankie Beverly \u00b7 Various artists |work=[[Spotify]]|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><br><small>(The Clark Sisters, [[J. Moss]], [[Kierra Sheard]])</small>\n| ''Silky Soul Music...an All-star Tribute to [[Maze (band)|Maze]] featuring [[Frankie Beverly]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[The First Noel]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/a-mary-christmas/1440819962|title=\t\nA Mary Christmas by Mary J. Blige on Apple Music|work=[[Apple Music]]|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><br><small>([[Mary J. Blige]] featuring the Clark Sisters)</small>\n| 2013\n| ''[[A Mary Christmas]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Hey Devil!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/let-them-fall-in-love/1168821004|title=\t\nLet Them Fall in Love by CeCe Winans on Apple Music|work=[[Apple Music]]|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><br><small>([[CeCe Winans]] featuring the Clark Sisters)</small>\n| 2017\n| ''[[Let Them Fall in Love]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Blessed & Highly Favored (Remix)\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/snoop-dogg-presents-bible-of-love/1341747511|title=\t\nSnoop Dogg Presents Bible of Love by Snoop Dogg on Apple Music|work=[[Apple Music]]|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><br><small>([[Snoop Dogg]] featuring the Clark Sisters)</small>\n| 2018\n| ''[[Bible of Love]]''\n|}\n\n==Covers==\n* One of the Clark Sisters' signature songs \"Is My Living in Vain\" was remade by R&B quartet [[Xscape (band)|Xscape]] on their debut album, [[Hummin' Comin' at 'Cha]], as well as [[Light Records]] gospel quartet [[Zie'l]].\n* An early Clark Sisters favorite \"Endow Me\" from their chart topping album ''[[You Brought the Sunshine]]'' was remade by [[Coko]] featuring [[Faith Evans]], [[Fantasia Barrino|Fantasia]], and [[Lil' Mo]] on her 2006 gospel debut \"Grateful\".\n* \"You Brought the Sunshine\" has been covered by artists such as [[Al Green]], [[Kelly Price]], [[Shirley Murdock]], [[Out of Eden]], [[Melinda Doolittle]], and LeJeune Thompson.\n* The ending vamp of the song \"''I've Got An Angel''\" from the 1986 release, \"Heart & Soul\" album of the Clark Sisters was used by [[Aaliyah]] in the song \"Never Givin' Up\" off of her 1996 album \"[[One in a Million (Aaliyah album)|One in a Million]]\".\n* \"Hallelujah\" from the Clark Sisters was sung in the [[Derek Luke (actor)|Derek Luke]] film ''[[Antwone Fisher (film)|Antwone Fisher]]'', starring [[Denzel Washington]].\n* Mary J. Blige sampled the Clark Sisters' \"They Were Overcome (By the Word)\" from their \"Is My Living in Vain\" album from 1980. She used the sample on \"Checkin' for Me,\" from her 2001 smash album, \"[[No More Drama]].\"\n*Rapper Jay-Z sampled their song \"Ha-Ya (Eternal Life)\", as well as Beyonc\u00e9's vocals covering the song, on the track \"Family Feud\" on his album, ''[[4:44 (album)|4:44]]''.\n* The Clark Sisters' \"They Were Overcome (By the Word)\" was sampled by Kierra Sheard on the track \"2nd Win\". \"There Is a Balm in Gilead\" and \"He'll Turn Your Scars into Stars\" from \"Heart and Soul\" was also sampled as interludes, from her 2014 album \"''Graceland''\".\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.theclarksisters.net}}\n* [https://www.myspace.com/officiallytheclarksisters Clark Sisters Official Myspace Page]\n* [http://clarkspace.activeboard.com The Clark Sisters Official Message Board]\n* [https://www.myspace.com/theclarkmarathon Clark Sisters Marathon on Myspace]\n* [http://www.live365.com/stations/love4myclarks Clark Sisters Internet Radio Station] on [[Live365]]\n* [http://www.thestellarawards.com Stellar Awards]\n* [http://blackgospel.com/alerts/clarksisters/liveonelasttime-le/ Clark Sisters: Live, One Last Time] (Release Alert on BlackGospel.com)\n\n{{The Clark Sisters}}\n{{Moss-Clark-Sheard}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clark Sisters, The}}\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:American gospel musical groups]]\n[[Category:Singers from Detroit]]\n[[Category:American gospel singers]]\n[[Category:Sibling musical groups]]\n[[Category:African-American musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Detroit]]\n[[Category:African-American Christians]]\n[[Category:American Pentecostals]]\n[[Category:Members of the Church of God in Christ]]\n[[Category:American girl groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1966]]\n[[Category:1966 establishments in Michigan]]\n", "name_user": "JonathanLGardner", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSingles", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Clark_Sisters"}
{"title_page": "Plague doctor", "text_new": "{{short description|The plague doctor was a Medical physician that treated patients with the death/bubonic plague}}\n[[File:Paul F\u00fcrst, Der Doctor Schnabel von Rom (coloured version).png|thumb|Copper engraving of Doctor Schnabel (i.e., Dr. Beak), a plague doctor in seventeenth-century Rome, circa 1656]]A '''plague doctor''' was a medical [[physician]] who treated victims of [[Black Death|the bubonic plague]].{{sfn|Cipolla|1977|p=65}}  In times of [[epidemic]]s, these physicians were specifically hired by towns where the plague had taken hold. Since the city was paying their salary, they treated everyone: both the wealthy and the poor.{{sfn|Cipolla|1977|p=68}} \n\nHowever, some plague doctors were known to charge patients and their families additional fees for special treatments or false cures.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rosenhek|first1=Jackie|title=Doctors of the Black Death|url=http://www.doctorsreview.com/history/doctors-black-death/|website=Doctor's Review|date=October 2011|access-date=2014-05-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506181745/http://www.doctorsreview.com/history/doctors-black-death/|archive-date=2014-05-06|url-status=live}}</ref> Typically, they  were not experienced physicians or [[surgeon]]s at all; rather, they were often either second-rate doctors unable to otherwise run a successful medical practice or young physicians seeking to establish themselves in the industry.{{sfn|Cipolla|1977|p=65}} They rarely cured their patients; rather, they served to record a count of the number of people contaminated for demographic purposes.\n\nPlague doctors by [[plague doctor contract|their covenant]] treated plague patients and were known as municipal or \"community plague doctors\", whereas \"general practitioners\" were separate doctors and both might be in the same European city or town at the same time.{{sfn|Cipolla|1977|p=65}}<ref>Ellis, Oliver C., ''A History of Fire and Flame 1932 '', Kessinger Publishing, 2004, p. 202. {{ISBN|1-4179-7583-0}}</ref><ref name=\"Byrne169\">Byrne (Daily), p. 169</ref><ref>Simon, Matthew, ''Emergent Computation: emphasizing bioinformatics'', Publisher \u30b7\u30e5\u30d7\u30ea\u30f3\u30ac\u30fc\u30fb\u30b8\u30e3\u30d1\u30f3\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e, 2005, p. 3. {{ISBN|0-387-22046-1}}</ref> In [[France]] and the [[Netherlands]], plague doctors often lacked medical training and were referred to as \"[[empiricism|empirics]]\". In one case, a plague doctor had been a fruit salesman before his employment as a physician.<ref name=\"Byrne170\">Byrne, 170</ref>\n\nIn the 17th, 18th, and 19th centuries, some doctors wore a beak-like mask which was filled with aromatic items. The masks were designed to protect them from putrid air, which (according to the [[Miasma theory|miasmatic theory]] of disease) was seen as the cause of infection. The design of these clothes has been attributed to [[Charles de Lorme]], the chief physician to [[Louis XIII]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The \"Science\" Behind Today's Plague Doctor Clothes|url=http://io9.gizmodo.com/the-science-behind-todays-plague-doctor-costume-1737404375|website=Gizmodo|date=June 2017|access-date=2017-08-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809130854/http://io9.gizmodo.com/the-science-behind-todays-plague-doctor-costume-1737404375|archive-date=2017-08-09|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe agga first European epidemic of the [[bubonic plague]] dates back to the mid 6th century and is called the [[Plague of Justinian]].<ref>Gordon, Benjamin Lemer, ''Medieval and Renaissance medicine'', Philosophical Library, 1959. p. 471</ref> The largest plague epidemic was the [[Black Death]] in Europe in the 14th century. The large losses of people in a town created an economic disaster, so community plague doctors were considered quite valuable and were given special privileges; for example, plague doctors were freely allowed to perform [[autopsies]] to research a cure for the plague.<ref>{{cite book|last=Wray|first=Shona Kelly|title=Communities and Crisis: Bologna During the Black Death|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ectUdDRhQjoC|year=2009|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-17634-9}}</ref>\n\nIn some cases, plague doctors were so valuable that when [[Barcelona]] dispatched two to [[Tortosa]] in 1650, outlaws captured them ''en route'' and demanded a ransom. Barcelona paid for their release.<ref name=\"Byrne169\" /> The city of [[Orvieto]] hired Matteo fu Angelo in 1348 for four times the normal rate of a doctor of 50-[[florin]] per year.<ref name=\"Byrne169\"/> [[Pope Clement VI]] hired several extra plague doctors during the [[Black Death]] plague to attend to the sick people of [[Avignon]]. Of 18 doctors in [[Venice]], only one was left by 1348: five had died of the plague, and 12 were missing and may have fled.<ref>Byrne, 168</ref>\n\n== Costume ==\n[[File:Medico peste.jpg|thumb|Plague doctor outfit from Germany (17th century).]]\n[[File:Beak doctor mask.jpg|thumb|upright|A beaked [[Carnival of Venice|Venetian carnival]] mask with the inscription ''Medico della Peste'' (\"Plague doctor\") beneath the right eye]]\n{{Main|Plague doctor costume}}\nSome plague doctors wore a [[Plague doctor costume|special costume]]. The garments were invented by [[Charles de L'Orme]] in 1630, and were first used in Naples, but later spread to be used throughout Europe.<ref>Christine M. Boeckl, ''Images of plague and pestilence: iconography and iconology'' (Truman State University Press, 2000), pp. 15, 27.</ref> The protective suit consisted of a light, waxed fabric overcoat, a mask with [[glass]] eye openings and a [[beak]] shaped nose, typically stuffed with herbs, straw, and spices. Plague doctors would also commonly carry a cane to examine and direct patients without the need to make direct contact with the patient.<ref>Byrne (Encyclopedia), p. 505</ref>\n\nThe scented materials included [[juniper berry]], [[ambergris]], [[roses]] (Rosa), [[Mentha spicata|mint]] (''Mentha spicata'' L.) leaves, [[camphor]], [[cloves]], [[laudanum]], [[myrrh]], and [[storax balsam|storax]].<ref name=\"Byrne170\" /> Due to the primitive understanding of disease at the time, it was believed this suit would sufficiently protect the doctor from [[Miasma theory of disease|miasma]] while tending to patients.<ref name=\"Loudon\">[[Irvine Loudon]], ''Western Medicine: An Illustrated History'' (Oxford, 2001), p. 189.</ref>\n\n== Public servants ==\nTheir principal task, besides taking care of people with the plague, was to record in public records the deaths due to the plague.<ref name=\"Byrne170\" />\n\nIn certain European cities like [[Florence]] and [[Perugia]], plague doctors were requested to do [[autopsies]] to help determine the cause of death and how the plague played a role.{{sfn|Wray|2009|p=172}} Plague doctors became witnesses to numerous wills during times of plague epidemics.{{sfn|Wray|2009|p=173}} Plague doctors also gave advice to their patients about their conduct before death.<ref name=\"jhmasextract276\">{{cite web |url=http://jhmas.oxfordjournals.org/content/XX/3/276.extract |title=The Plague Doctor |publisher=Jhmas.oxfordjournals.org |date=2012-04-02 |accessdate=2012-06-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130212013047/http://jhmas.oxfordjournals.org/content/XX/3/276.extract |archive-date=2013-02-12 |url-status=live }}</ref> This advice varied depending on the patient, and after the [[Middle Ages]], the nature of the relationship between doctor and patient was governed by an increasingly complex ethical code.{{sfn|Gottfried|1983|p=126}}{{sfn|Gottfried|1983|p=127-128}}\n\n== Methods ==\nPlague doctors practiced [[bloodletting]] and other remedies such as putting [[frogs]] or [[leeches]] on the [[bubo]]es to \"rebalance [[Humorism|the humors]]\" as a normal routine.<ref>Byfield, Ted, ''Renaissance: God in Man, A.D. 1300 to 1500: But Amid Its Splendors, Night Falls on Medieval Christianity'', Christian History Project, 2010, p. 37. {{ISBN|0-9689873-8-9}}</ref> Plague doctors could not generally interact with the general public because of the nature of their business and the possibility of spreading the disease; they could also be subject to [[quarantine]].{{sfn|Gottfried|1983|p=126}} \n\n== Notable Renaissance plague doctors ==\nA famous plague doctor who gave medical advice about preventive measures which could be used against the plague was [[Nostradamus]].<ref>Hogue, John,''Nostradamus: the new revelations'', Barnes & Noble Books, 1995, p. 1884. {{ISBN|1-56619-948-4}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ADri5RCWu-UC&pg=PT21&dq=Nostradamus+was+a+plague+doctor#v=onepage&q=Nostradamus%20was%20a%20plague%20doctor&f=false |title=The essential Nostradamus: literal translation, historical commentary, and ... By Richard Smoley |date= 2006-01-19|accessdate=2012-06-12|isbn=978-1-4406-4984-4 |last1=Smoley |first1=Richard }}</ref> Nostradamus' advice was the removal of infected corpses, getting fresh air, drinking clean water, and drinking a juice preparation of [[rose hips]].<ref>Pickover, Clifford A., ''Dreaming the Future: the fantastic story of prediction'', Prometheus Books, 2001, p. 279. {{ISBN|1-57392-895-X}}</ref><ref name=\"Trait\u00e9\">{{cite web |url=http://www.propheties.it/bibliotheque/1539-1567/1555-003%20Nostradamus,%20Excellent%20&%20moult%20utile/index.html |title=Excellent et moult utile opuscule \u00e0 tous/ n\u00e9cessaire qui d\u00e9sirent avoir connoissan/ ce de plusieurs exquises receptes divis\u00e9/ en deux parties./ La premi\u00e8re traicte de diverses fa\u00e7ons/ de fardemens et senteurs pour illustrer et/ embelir la face./ La seconde nous montre la fa\u00e7on et/ mani\u00e8re de faire confitures de plusieurs/ sortes... Nouvellement compos\u00e9 par Maistre/ Michel de NOSTREDAME docteur/ en medecine... by Nostradamus |publisher=Propheties.it |accessdate=2012-06-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317155633/http://www.propheties.it/bibliotheque/1539-1567/1555-003%20Nostradamus%2C%20Excellent%20%26%20moult%20utile/index.html |archivedate=2012-03-17 }}</ref> In ''[[Trait\u00e9 des fardemens]]'' it shows in Part A Chapter VIII that Nostradamus also recommended ''not'' to [[Bloodletting|bleed]] the patient.<ref name=\"Trait\u00e9\" />\n\nThe Italian city of [[Pavia]], in 1479, contracted [[Giovanni de Ventura]] as a community plague doctor.<ref name=\"Byrne169\" /><ref>King, Margaret L., ''Western Civilization: a social and cultural history'', Prentice-Hall, 2002, p. 339. {{ISBN|0-13-045007-3}}</ref> The Irish [[physician]], [[Niall \u00d3 Glac\u00e1in]] (c.1563?\u20131653) earned deep respect in Spain, France and Italy for his bravery in treating numerous people with the plague.<ref>Stephen, p. 927</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|pmc=2385830 |title=THE HISTORY OF MEDICINE IN IRELAND; by J. OLIVER WOODS, MD, FRCGP, Page 40 |format=PDF |date= |pmid=6761926 |volume=51 |issue=1 |year=1982 |journal=Ulster Med J |pages=35\u201345 |author=Woods JO}}</ref> The French anatomist [[Ambroise Par\u00e9]] and Swiss [[Iatrochemistry|iatrochemist]] [[Paracelsus]], were also famous Renaissance plague doctors.<ref>K\u00f6rner, Christian, ''Mountain Biodiversity: a global assessment'', CRC Press, 2002, p. 13. {{ISBN|1-84214-091-4}}</ref>\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Primary sources ===\n* Nostradamus. ''The Prophecies of Nostradamus'', self-published 1555 & 1558; reprinted by [https://books.google.com/books?id=XQdY0lGFJX0C&dq=Nostradamus+Black+Death&source=gbs_navlinks_s Forgotten Books publishing 1973], {{ISBN|1-60506-507-2}}\n* Nostradamus. ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20120317155633/http://www.propheties.it/bibliotheque/1539-1567/1555-003%20Nostradamus%2C%20Excellent%20%26%20moult%20utile/index.html Trait\u00e9 des fardemens et confitures]'' self-published 1555\n\n=== Secondary sources ===\n{{Commons category|Plague doctors}}\n* Bauer, S. Wise, ''The Story of the World Activity Book Two: The Middle Ages : From the Fall of Rome to the Rise of the Renaissance'', Peace Hill Press, 2003, {{ISBN|0-9714129-4-4}}\n* Byrne, Joseph Patrick, ''Daily Life during the Black Death'', Greenwood Publishing Group, 2006, {{ISBN|0-313-33297-5}}\n* Byrne, Joseph Patrick, ''Encyclopedia of Pestilence, Pandemics, and Plagues'', ABC-Clio, 2008, {{ISBN|0-313-34102-8}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=Cipolla |first=Carlo M. |title=A Plague Doctor |editor-first=Harry A. |editor-last=Miskimin |chapter=The Medieval City |publisher=[[Yale University Press]] |year=1977 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/medievalcity00misk/page/65 65\u201372] |isbn=978-0-300-02081-6 |url=https://archive.org/details/medievalcity00misk/page/65 }}\n* Fee, Elizabeth, ''AIDS: the burdens of history'', University of California Press, 1988, {{ISBN|0-520-06396-1}}\n* Haggard, Howard W., ''From Medicine Man to Doctor: The Story of the Science of Healing'', Courier Dover Publications, 2004, {{ISBN|0-486-43541-5}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |first=Robert S. |last=Gottfried |title=The Black Death: natural and human disaster in medieval Europe |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |year=1983 |pages=126\u201328}}\n* Heymann, David L., ''The World Health Report 2007: a safer future : global public health security in the 21st century'', World Health Organization, 2007, {{ISBN|92-4-156344-3}}\n* Kenda, Barbara, ''Aeolian winds and the spirit in Renaissance architecture: Academia Eolia revisited'', Taylor & Francis, 2006, {{ISBN|0-415-39804-5}}\n* O'Donnell, Terence, ''History of Life Insurance in its Formative Years'', American Conservation Company, 1936\n* Pommerville, Jeffrey, ''Alcamo's Fundamentals of Microbiology'', Jones & Bartlett Learning, 2010, {{ISBN|0-7637-6258-X}}\n* Reading, Mario, ''The Complete Prophecies of Nostradamus'', Sterling Publishing (2009), {{ISBN|1-906787-39-5}}\n* Stuart, David C., ''Dangerous Garden: the quest for plants to change our lives'', Frances Lincoln ltd, 2004, {{ISBN|0-7112-2265-7}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=Wray |first=Shona Kelly |title=Communities and Crisis: Bologna during the Black Death |isbn=978-90-04-17634-8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4imwCQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover |publisher=[[Brill (publisher)|Brill]] |date=2 June 2009 |pages=312}}\n* Fitzharris, Lindsey. \"Behind the Mask: The Plague Doctor.\" The Chirurgeons Apprentice. Web. 6 May 2014.\n* Rosenhek, Jackie. \"Doctor's Review: Medicine on the Move.\" Doctor's Review. Web. May 2011.\n\n== External links ==\n* \n\n{{Portal bar|History|Medicine}}\n\n[[Category:Plague doctor| ]]\n[[Category:Black Death]]\n[[Category:History of medieval medicine]]\n[[Category:Obsolete occupations]]\n[[Category:Supernatural legends]]\n[[Category:Traditional healthcare occupations]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|The plague doctor was a Medical physician that treated patients with the death/bubonic plague}}\n[[File:Paul F\u00fcrst, Der Doctor Schnabel von Rom (coloured version).png|thumb|Copper engraving of Doctor Schnabel (i.e., Dr. Beak), a plague doctor in seventeenth-century Rome, circa 1656]]A '''plague doctor''' was a medical [[physician]] who treated victims of [[Black Death|the bubonic plague]].{{sfn|Cipolla|1977|p=65}}  In times of [[epidemic]]s, these physicians were specifically hired by towns where the plague had taken hold. Since the city was paying their salary, they treated everyone: both the wealthy and the poor.{{sfn|Cipolla|1977|p=68}} \n\nHowever, some plague doctors were known to charge patients and their families additional fees for special treatments or false cures.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rosenhek|first1=Jackie|title=Doctors of the Black Death|url=http://www.doctorsreview.com/history/doctors-black-death/|website=Doctor's Review|date=October 2011|access-date=2014-05-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506181745/http://www.doctorsreview.com/history/doctors-black-death/|archive-date=2014-05-06|url-status=live}}</ref> Typically, they  were not experienced physicians or [[surgeon]]s at all; rather, they were often either second-rate doctors unable to otherwise run a successful medical practice or young physicians seeking to establish themselves in the industry.{{sfn|Cipolla|1977|p=65}} They rarely cured their patients; rather, they served to record a count of the number of people contaminated for demographic purposes.\n\nPlague doctors by [[plague doctor contract|their covenant]] treated plague patients and were known as municipal or \"community plague doctors\", whereas \"general practitioners\" were separate doctors and both might be in the same European city or town at the same time.{{sfn|Cipolla|1977|p=65}}<ref>Ellis, Oliver C., ''A History of Fire and Flame 1932 '', Kessinger Publishing, 2004, p. 202. {{ISBN|1-4179-7583-0}}</ref><ref name=\"Byrne169\">Byrne (Daily), p. 169</ref><ref>Simon, Matthew, ''Emergent Computation: emphasizing bioinformatics'', Publisher \u30b7\u30e5\u30d7\u30ea\u30f3\u30ac\u30fc\u30fb\u30b8\u30e3\u30d1\u30f3\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e, 2005, p. 3. {{ISBN|0-387-22046-1}}</ref> In [[France]] and the [[Netherlands]], plague doctors often lacked medical training and were referred to as \"[[empiricism|empirics]]\". In one case, a plague doctor had been a fruit salesman before his employment as a physician.<ref name=\"Byrne170\">Byrne, 170</ref>\n\nIn the 17th, 18th, and 19th centuries, some doctors wore a beak-like mask which was filled with aromatic items. The masks were designed to protect them from putrid air, which (according to the [[Miasma theory|miasmatic theory]] of disease) was seen as the cause of infection. The design of these clothes has been attributed to [[Charles de Lorme]], the chief physician to [[Louis XIII]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The \"Science\" Behind Today's Plague Doctor Clothes|url=http://io9.gizmodo.com/the-science-behind-todays-plague-doctor-costume-1737404375|website=Gizmodo|date=June 2017|access-date=2017-08-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809130854/http://io9.gizmodo.com/the-science-behind-todays-plague-doctor-costume-1737404375|archive-date=2017-08-09|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe first European epidemic of the [[bubonic plague]] dates back to the mid 6th century and is called the [[Plague of Justinian]].<ref>Gordon, Benjamin Lemer, ''Medieval and Renaissance medicine'', Philosophical Library, 1959. p. 471</ref> The largest plague epidemic was the [[Black Death]] in Europe in the 14th century. The large losses of people in a town created an economic disaster, so community plague doctors were considered quite valuable and were given special privileges; for example, plague doctors were freely allowed to perform [[autopsies]] to research a cure for the plague.<ref>{{cite book|last=Wray|first=Shona Kelly|title=Communities and Crisis: Bologna During the Black Death|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ectUdDRhQjoC|year=2009|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-17634-9}}</ref>\n\nIn some cases, plague doctors were so valuable that when [[Barcelona]] dispatched two to [[Tortosa]] in 1650, outlaws captured them ''en route'' and demanded a ransom. Barcelona paid for their release.<ref name=\"Byrne169\" /> The city of [[Orvieto]] hired Matteo fu Angelo in 1348 for four times the normal rate of a doctor of 50-[[florin]] per year.<ref name=\"Byrne169\"/> [[Pope Clement VI]] hired several extra plague doctors during the [[Black Death]] plague to attend to the sick people of [[Avignon]]. Of 18 doctors in [[Venice]], only one was left by 1348: five had died of the plague, and 12 were missing and may have fled.<ref>Byrne, 168</ref>\n\n== Costume ==\n[[File:Medico peste.jpg|thumb|Plague doctor outfit from Germany (17th century).]]\n[[File:Beak doctor mask.jpg|thumb|upright|A beaked [[Carnival of Venice|Venetian carnival]] mask with the inscription ''Medico della Peste'' (\"Plague doctor\") beneath the right eye]]\n{{Main|Plague doctor costume}}\nSome plague doctors wore a [[Plague doctor costume|special costume]]. The garments were invented by [[Charles de L'Orme]] in 1630, and were first used in Naples, but later spread to be used throughout Europe.<ref>Christine M. Boeckl, ''Images of plague and pestilence: iconography and iconology'' (Truman State University Press, 2000), pp. 15, 27.</ref> The protective suit consisted of a light, waxed fabric overcoat, a mask with [[glass]] eye openings and a [[beak]] shaped nose, typically stuffed with herbs, straw, and spices. Plague doctors would also commonly carry a cane to examine and direct patients without the need to make direct contact with the patient.<ref>Byrne (Encyclopedia), p. 505</ref>\n\nThe scented materials included [[juniper berry]], [[ambergris]], [[roses]] (Rosa), [[Mentha spicata|mint]] (''Mentha spicata'' L.) leaves, [[camphor]], [[cloves]], [[laudanum]], [[myrrh]], and [[storax balsam|storax]].<ref name=\"Byrne170\" /> Due to the primitive understanding of disease at the time, it was believed this suit would sufficiently protect the doctor from [[Miasma theory of disease|miasma]] while tending to patients.<ref name=\"Loudon\">[[Irvine Loudon]], ''Western Medicine: An Illustrated History'' (Oxford, 2001), p. 189.</ref>\n\n== Public servants ==\nTheir principal task, besides taking care of people with the plague, was to record in public records the deaths due to the plague.<ref name=\"Byrne170\" />\n\nIn certain European cities like [[Florence]] and [[Perugia]], plague doctors were requested to do [[autopsies]] to help determine the cause of death and how the plague played a role.{{sfn|Wray|2009|p=172}} Plague doctors became witnesses to numerous wills during times of plague epidemics.{{sfn|Wray|2009|p=173}} Plague doctors also gave advice to their patients about their conduct before death.<ref name=\"jhmasextract276\">{{cite web |url=http://jhmas.oxfordjournals.org/content/XX/3/276.extract |title=The Plague Doctor |publisher=Jhmas.oxfordjournals.org |date=2012-04-02 |accessdate=2012-06-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130212013047/http://jhmas.oxfordjournals.org/content/XX/3/276.extract |archive-date=2013-02-12 |url-status=live }}</ref> This advice varied depending on the patient, and after the [[Middle Ages]], the nature of the relationship between doctor and patient was governed by an increasingly complex ethical code.{{sfn|Gottfried|1983|p=126}}{{sfn|Gottfried|1983|p=127-128}}\n\n== Methods ==\nPlague doctors practiced [[bloodletting]] and other remedies such as putting [[frogs]] or [[leeches]] on the [[bubo]]es to \"rebalance [[Humorism|the humors]]\" as a normal routine.<ref>Byfield, Ted, ''Renaissance: God in Man, A.D. 1300 to 1500: But Amid Its Splendors, Night Falls on Medieval Christianity'', Christian History Project, 2010, p. 37. {{ISBN|0-9689873-8-9}}</ref> Plague doctors could not generally interact with the general public because of the nature of their business and the possibility of spreading the disease; they could also be subject to [[quarantine]].{{sfn|Gottfried|1983|p=126}} \n\n== Notable Renaissance plague doctors ==\nA famous plague doctor who gave medical advice about preventive measures which could be used against the plague was [[Nostradamus]].<ref>Hogue, John,''Nostradamus: the new revelations'', Barnes & Noble Books, 1995, p. 1884. {{ISBN|1-56619-948-4}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ADri5RCWu-UC&pg=PT21&dq=Nostradamus+was+a+plague+doctor#v=onepage&q=Nostradamus%20was%20a%20plague%20doctor&f=false |title=The essential Nostradamus: literal translation, historical commentary, and ... By Richard Smoley |date= 2006-01-19|accessdate=2012-06-12|isbn=978-1-4406-4984-4 |last1=Smoley |first1=Richard }}</ref> Nostradamus' advice was the removal of infected corpses, getting fresh air, drinking clean water, and drinking a juice preparation of [[rose hips]].<ref>Pickover, Clifford A., ''Dreaming the Future: the fantastic story of prediction'', Prometheus Books, 2001, p. 279. {{ISBN|1-57392-895-X}}</ref><ref name=\"Trait\u00e9\">{{cite web |url=http://www.propheties.it/bibliotheque/1539-1567/1555-003%20Nostradamus,%20Excellent%20&%20moult%20utile/index.html |title=Excellent et moult utile opuscule \u00e0 tous/ n\u00e9cessaire qui d\u00e9sirent avoir connoissan/ ce de plusieurs exquises receptes divis\u00e9/ en deux parties./ La premi\u00e8re traicte de diverses fa\u00e7ons/ de fardemens et senteurs pour illustrer et/ embelir la face./ La seconde nous montre la fa\u00e7on et/ mani\u00e8re de faire confitures de plusieurs/ sortes... Nouvellement compos\u00e9 par Maistre/ Michel de NOSTREDAME docteur/ en medecine... by Nostradamus |publisher=Propheties.it |accessdate=2012-06-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317155633/http://www.propheties.it/bibliotheque/1539-1567/1555-003%20Nostradamus%2C%20Excellent%20%26%20moult%20utile/index.html |archivedate=2012-03-17 }}</ref> In ''[[Trait\u00e9 des fardemens]]'' it shows in Part A Chapter VIII that Nostradamus also recommended ''not'' to [[Bloodletting|bleed]] the patient.<ref name=\"Trait\u00e9\" />\n\nThe Italian city of [[Pavia]], in 1479, contracted [[Giovanni de Ventura]] as a community plague doctor.<ref name=\"Byrne169\" /><ref>King, Margaret L., ''Western Civilization: a social and cultural history'', Prentice-Hall, 2002, p. 339. {{ISBN|0-13-045007-3}}</ref> The Irish [[physician]], [[Niall \u00d3 Glac\u00e1in]] (c.1563?\u20131653) earned deep respect in Spain, France and Italy for his bravery in treating numerous people with the plague.<ref>Stephen, p. 927</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|pmc=2385830 |title=THE HISTORY OF MEDICINE IN IRELAND; by J. OLIVER WOODS, MD, FRCGP, Page 40 |format=PDF |date= |pmid=6761926 |volume=51 |issue=1 |year=1982 |journal=Ulster Med J |pages=35\u201345 |author=Woods JO}}</ref> The French anatomist [[Ambroise Par\u00e9]] and Swiss [[Iatrochemistry|iatrochemist]] [[Paracelsus]], were also famous Renaissance plague doctors.<ref>K\u00f6rner, Christian, ''Mountain Biodiversity: a global assessment'', CRC Press, 2002, p. 13. {{ISBN|1-84214-091-4}}</ref>\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Primary sources ===\n* Nostradamus. ''The Prophecies of Nostradamus'', self-published 1555 & 1558; reprinted by [https://books.google.com/books?id=XQdY0lGFJX0C&dq=Nostradamus+Black+Death&source=gbs_navlinks_s Forgotten Books publishing 1973], {{ISBN|1-60506-507-2}}\n* Nostradamus. ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20120317155633/http://www.propheties.it/bibliotheque/1539-1567/1555-003%20Nostradamus%2C%20Excellent%20%26%20moult%20utile/index.html Trait\u00e9 des fardemens et confitures]'' self-published 1555\n\n=== Secondary sources ===\n{{Commons category|Plague doctors}}\n* Bauer, S. Wise, ''The Story of the World Activity Book Two: The Middle Ages : From the Fall of Rome to the Rise of the Renaissance'', Peace Hill Press, 2003, {{ISBN|0-9714129-4-4}}\n* Byrne, Joseph Patrick, ''Daily Life during the Black Death'', Greenwood Publishing Group, 2006, {{ISBN|0-313-33297-5}}\n* Byrne, Joseph Patrick, ''Encyclopedia of Pestilence, Pandemics, and Plagues'', ABC-Clio, 2008, {{ISBN|0-313-34102-8}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=Cipolla |first=Carlo M. |title=A Plague Doctor |editor-first=Harry A. |editor-last=Miskimin |chapter=The Medieval City |publisher=[[Yale University Press]] |year=1977 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/medievalcity00misk/page/65 65\u201372] |isbn=978-0-300-02081-6 |url=https://archive.org/details/medievalcity00misk/page/65 }}\n* Fee, Elizabeth, ''AIDS: the burdens of history'', University of California Press, 1988, {{ISBN|0-520-06396-1}}\n* Haggard, Howard W., ''From Medicine Man to Doctor: The Story of the Science of Healing'', Courier Dover Publications, 2004, {{ISBN|0-486-43541-5}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |first=Robert S. |last=Gottfried |title=The Black Death: natural and human disaster in medieval Europe |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |year=1983 |pages=126\u201328}}\n* Heymann, David L., ''The World Health Report 2007: a safer future : global public health security in the 21st century'', World Health Organization, 2007, {{ISBN|92-4-156344-3}}\n* Kenda, Barbara, ''Aeolian winds and the spirit in Renaissance architecture: Academia Eolia revisited'', Taylor & Francis, 2006, {{ISBN|0-415-39804-5}}\n* O'Donnell, Terence, ''History of Life Insurance in its Formative Years'', American Conservation Company, 1936\n* Pommerville, Jeffrey, ''Alcamo's Fundamentals of Microbiology'', Jones & Bartlett Learning, 2010, {{ISBN|0-7637-6258-X}}\n* Reading, Mario, ''The Complete Prophecies of Nostradamus'', Sterling Publishing (2009), {{ISBN|1-906787-39-5}}\n* Stuart, David C., ''Dangerous Garden: the quest for plants to change our lives'', Frances Lincoln ltd, 2004, {{ISBN|0-7112-2265-7}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=Wray |first=Shona Kelly |title=Communities and Crisis: Bologna during the Black Death |isbn=978-90-04-17634-8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4imwCQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover |publisher=[[Brill (publisher)|Brill]] |date=2 June 2009 |pages=312}}\n* Fitzharris, Lindsey. \"Behind the Mask: The Plague Doctor.\" The Chirurgeons Apprentice. Web. 6 May 2014.\n* Rosenhek, Jackie. \"Doctor's Review: Medicine on the Move.\" Doctor's Review. Web. May 2011.\n\n== External links ==\n* \n\n{{Portal bar|History|Medicine}}\n\n[[Category:Plague doctor| ]]\n[[Category:Black Death]]\n[[Category:History of medieval medicine]]\n[[Category:Obsolete occupations]]\n[[Category:Supernatural legends]]\n[[Category:Traditional healthcare occupations]]\n", "name_user": "79.79.141.111", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plague_doctor"}
{"title_page": "34th Annual Grammy Awards", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=May 2011}}\n{{Infobox award\n| name     = 34th Annual Grammy Awards\n| image    = \n| caption  = \n| date     = February 25, 1992\n| location = [[Radio City Music Hall]], [[New York City]]\n| host     = [[Whoopi Goldberg]]\n| network  = CBS\n| previous = [[33rd Annual Grammy Awards|33rd]]\n| main     = [[Grammy&nbsp;Award]]s\n| next     = [[35th Annual Grammy Awards|35th]]\n}}\nThe '''34th Annual Grammy Awards''' were held on February 25, 1992<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/02/26/arts/cole-s-unforgettable-sweeps-the-grammys.html?src=pm|title=Cole's 'Unforgettable' Sweeps the Grammys|author=Pareles, Jon|date=26 February 1992|work=The New York Times|accessdate=26 September 2012}}</ref>, recognizing accomplishments by musicians from the previous year (1991). [[Natalie Cole]] won the most awards (three), including [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ILJRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=SW4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=3240,6416393&dq=grammy&hl=en|title=Natalie Cole emotional favorite at Grammys|author=Campbell, Mary|date=26 February 1992|publisher=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|accessdate=1 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=&title=&year=1991&genre=All|title=1991 Grammy Award Winners|publisher=Grammy.com|accessdate=1 May 2011}}</ref> [[Paul Simon (musician)|Paul Simon]] opened the show.\n\n==Award winners==\n*[[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]]\n**[[David Foster]] (producer) for \"[[Unforgettable (Nat King Cole song)|Unforgettable]]\" performed by [[Natalie Cole]] with [[Nat King Cole]]\n*[[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]]\n**[[Rufus (band)|Andr\u00e9 Fischer]], [[David Foster]] & [[Tommy LiPuma]] (producers) for ''[[Unforgettable... with Love]]'' performed by [[Natalie Cole]]\n*[[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]]\n**[[Irving Gordon]] (songwriter) for \"[[Unforgettable (Nat King Cole song)|Unforgettable]]\" performed by [[Natalie Cole]] with [[Nat King Cole]]\n*[[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]]\n**[[Marc Cohn]]\n\n===Alternative===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Alternative Music Album|Best Alternative Music Album]]\n**[[R.E.M.]] for ''[[Out of Time (album)|Out of Time]]''\n\n===Blues===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Traditional Blues Album|Best Traditional Blues Album]]\n**[[B.B. King]] for ''[[Live at the Apollo (B. B. King album)|Live at the Apollo]]'' \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Blues Album|Best Contemporary Blues Album]]\n**[[Buddy Guy]] for ''[[Damn Right, I've Got the Blues]]''\n\n===Children's===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Album for Children|Best Album for Children]]\n**Clifford \"Barney\" Robertson (producer) for ''A Capella Kids'' performed by The Maranatha! Kids\n\n===Classical===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Orchestral Performance|Best Orchestral Performance]]\n**[[Daniel Barenboim]] (conductor) & the [[Chicago Symphony Orchestra]] for ''[[John Corigliano|Corigliano]]: Symphony No. 1''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Classical Vocal Performance|Best Classical Vocal Soloist]]\n**[[Dawn Upshaw]] for ''The Girl With Orange Lips ([[Manuel de Falla|Falla]], [[Maurice Ravel|Ravel]], etc.)''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Opera Recording|Best Opera Recording]]\n**Cord Garben (producer), [[James Levine]] (conductor), [[Hildegard Behrens]], [[Reiner Goldberg]], [[Matti Salminen]], [[Hanna Schwarz]], [[Cheryl Studer]], [[Bernd Weikl]], [[Ekkehard Wlaschiha]], & the [[Metropolitan Opera Orchestra]] for ''[[Richard Wagner|Wagner]]: G\u00f6tterd\u00e4mmerung''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Choral Performance|Best Performance of a Choral Work]]\n**[[Georg Solti]] (conductor), [[Margaret Hillis]] (choir director) & the [[Chicago Symphony Orchestra|Chicago Symphony Orchestra & Chorus]] for ''[[Johann Sebastian Bach|Bach]]: Mass in B Minor''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Instrumental Soloist(s) Performance (with orchestra)|Best Instrumental Soloist With Orchestra]]\n**[[Leonard Slatkin]] (conductor), [[John Browning (pianist)|John Browning]] & the [[Saint Louis Symphony Orchestra]] for ''[[Samuel Barber|Barber]]: Piano Concerto''  \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Instrumental Soloist Performance (without orchestra)|Best Classical Performance Instrumental Solo Without Orchestra]]\n**[[Alicia de Larrocha]] for ''[[Enrique Granados|Granados]]: Goyescas; Allegro de Concierto; Danza Lenta''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Chamber Music Performance|Best Chamber Music Performance]]\n**[[Emanuel Ax]], [[Jaime Laredo]], [[Yo-Yo Ma]] & [[Isaac Stern]] for ''[[Johannes Brahms|Brahms]]: Piano Quartets (Opp. 25 and 26)''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Classical Contemporary Composition|Best Contemporary Composition]]\n**[[John Corigliano]] (composer), [[Daniel Barenboim]] (conductor) & the [[Chicago Symphony Orchestra]] for ''Corigliano: Symphony No. 1''  \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Classical Album|Best Classical Album]]\n**[[Hans Weber]] (producer), [[Leonard Bernstein]] (conductor), [[June Anderson]], [[Nicolai Gedda]], [[Adolph Green]], [[Jerry Hadley]], [[Della Jones]], [[Christa Ludwig]], [[Kurt Ollmann]] & the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] for ''Bernstein: Candide''\n\n===Comedy===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Comedy Album|Best Comedy Album]]\n**[[Peter Schickele]] for ''P.D.Q. Bach: [[WTWP Classical Talkity-Talk Radio]]''\n\n===Composing and arranging===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Instrumental Composition|Best Instrumental Composition]]\n**[[Elton John]] (composer) for \"Basque\" performed by [[James Galway]]        \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media|Best Song Written Specifically for a Motion Picture or Television]]\n**[[Bryan Adams]], [[Michael Kamen]] & [[Robert Lange|Robert John \"Mutt\" Lange]] (songwriters) for \"[[(Everything I Do) I Do It for You]]\" performed by Bryan Adams  \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Score Soundtrack Album for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media|Best Instrumental Composition Written for a Motion Picture or for Television]]\n**[[John Barry (composer)|John Barry]] (composer) for ''[[Dances With Wolves]]''  \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Instrumental Arrangement|Best Arrangement on an Instrumental]]\n**[[Dave Grusin]] (arranger) for \"[[The Gershwin Connection#Track listing|Medley: Bess You Is My Woman/I Loves You Porgy]]\"\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocalist(s)|Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocal(s)]]\n**[[Johnny Mandel]] (arranger) for \"[[Unforgettable (Nat King Cole song)|Unforgettable]]\" performed by [[Natalie Cole]] with [[Nat King Cole]]\n\n===Country===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Female Country Vocal Performance|Best Country Vocal Performance, Female]]\n**[[Mary Chapin Carpenter]] for \"[[Down at the Twist and Shout]]\"\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Male Country Vocal Performance|Best Country Vocal Performance, Male]]\n**[[Garth Brooks]] for ''[[Ropin' the Wind]]''  \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Country Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal|Best Country Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal]]\n**[[The Judds]] for \"[[Love Can Build a Bridge]]\"\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Country Collaboration with Vocals|Best Country Vocal Collaboration]]\n**[[Vince Gill]], [[Ricky Skaggs]] & [[Steve Wariner]] for \"[[Restless (Carl Perkins song)|Restless]]\"\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Country Instrumental Performance|Best Country Instrumental Performance]]\n**[[Mark O'Connor]] for ''[[The New Nashville Cats]]''  \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Country Song|Best Country Song]]\n**[[John Barlow Jarvis|John Jarvis]], [[Naomi Judd]] & [[Paul Overstreet]] (songwriters) for \"[[Love Can Build a Bridge]]\" performed by [[The Judds]]  \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Bluegrass Album|Best Bluegrass Album]]\n**[[Carl Jackson]] & John Starling for ''Spring Training''\n\n===Folk===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Traditional Folk Album|Best Traditional Folk Album]]\n**[[Ken Burns]] & [[John Colby (musician)|John Colby]] (producers) for ''[[The Civil War (TV series)#Soundtrack|The Civil War - Original Soundtrack]]'' performed by various artists  \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Folk Album|Best Contemporary Folk Album]]\n**[[John Prine]] for ''[[The Missing Years (album)|The Missing Years]]''\n\n===Gospel===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Pop/Contemporary Gospel Album|Best Pop Gospel Album]]\n**[[Steven Curtis Chapman]] for ''For the Sake of the Call''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Rock Gospel Album|Best Rock/Contemporary Gospel Album]]\n**[[Russ Taff]] for ''Under Their Influence''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Traditional Soul Gospel Album|Best Traditional Soul Gospel Album]]\n**[[Mighty Clouds of Joy]] for ''Pray For Me''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Soul Gospel Album|Best Contemporary Soul Gospel Album]]\n**[[BeBe Winans]] & [[CeCe Winans]] for ''Different Lifestyles'' \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Southern, Country or Bluegrass Gospel Album|Best Southern Gospel Album]]\n**The [[Gaither Vocal Band]] for ''Homecoming'' \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Gospel Choir or Chorus Album|Best Gospel Album by Choir or Chorus]]\n**Gary Hines (choir director) for ''The Evolution of Gospel'' performed by The [[Sounds of Blackness]]\n\n===Historical===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Historical Album|Best Historical Album]]\n**Steven Lasker & Andy McKaie (producers) for [[Billie Holiday]] - ''The Complete Decca Recordings''\n\n===Jazz===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Jazz Instrumental Solo|Best Jazz Instrumental Solo]]\n**[[Stan Getz]] for \"I Remember You\"\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Jazz Instrumental Album, Individual or Group|Best Jazz Instrumental Performance, Group]]\n**The [[Oscar Peterson Trio]] for ''[[Saturday Night at the Blue Note]]''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Large Jazz Ensemble Album|Best Large Jazz Ensemble Performance]]\n**[[Dizzy Gillespie]] for ''[[Live at the Royal Festival Hall (Dizzy Gillespie album)|Live at the Royal Festival Hall]]''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Jazz Vocal Album|Best Jazz Vocal Performance]]\n**[[Take 6]] for ''[[He Is Christmas]]''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Jazz Album|Best Contemporary Jazz Performance]]\n**[[The Manhattan Transfer]] for \"[[The Offbeat of Avenues|Sassy]]\"\n\n===Latin===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop Album|Best Latin Pop Album]]\n**[[Vikki Carr]] for ''[[Cosas del Amor (Vikki Carr album)|Cosas del Amor]] '' \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Traditional Tropical Latin Album|Best Tropical Latin Album]]\n**[[Juan Luis Guerra]] for ''[[Bachata Rosa]]''  \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Mexican/Mexican-American Album|Best Mexican-American Album]]\n**[[Little Joe (singer)|Little Joe]] for ''[[16 de Septiembre]]''\n\n===Musical show===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Musical Show Album|Best Musical Show Album]]\n**[[Cy Coleman]] (producer and composer), [[Mike Berniker]] (producer), [[Adolph Green]], [[Betty Comden]] (lyricists) & the original Broadway cast for ''[[The Will Rogers Follies]]''\n\n===Music video===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Short Form Music Video|Best Music Video, Short Form]]\n**[[Tarsem]] (video director) & [[R.E.M.]] for \"[[Losing My Religion]]\"\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Long Form Music Video|Best Music Video, Long Form]]\n**[[Anthony Eaton]] (video producer), [[David Mallet (director)|David Mallet]], Mark \"Aldo\" Miceli (video directors) & [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] for ''Madonna:  [[Blond Ambition World Tour Live]]''\n\n===New Age===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best New Age Album|Best New Age Album]]\n**[[Chip Davis]] for ''[[Fresh Aire 7]]''\n\n===Packaging and notes===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Recording Package|Best Album Package]]\n**Vartan (art director) for ''Billie Holiday - The Complete Decca Recordings''  performed by [[Billie Holiday]] \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Album Notes|Best Album Notes]]\n**Alan M. Leeds, Cliff White, Harry Weinger, [[James Brown (musician)|James Brown]] & [[Nelson George]] (notes writers) for ''[[Star Time]]'' performed by James Brown\n\n===Polka===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Polka Album|Best Polka Album]]\n**[[Jimmy Sturr]] for ''[[Live at Gilley's!]]''\n\n===Pop===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Female Pop Vocal Performance|Best Pop Vocal Performance, Female]]\n**[[Bonnie Raitt]] for \"[[Something to Talk About (Bonnie Raitt song)|Something to Talk About]]\"\n\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Male Pop Vocal Performance|Best Pop Vocal Performance, Male]]\n**[[Michael Bolton]] for \"[[When a Man Loves a Woman (song)|When a Man Loves a Woman]]\"\n\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Pop Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal|Best Pop Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal]]\n**[[R.E.M.]] for \"[[Losing My Religion]]\"\n\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Pop Instrumental Performance|Best Pop Instrumental Performance]]\n**[[Michael Kamen]] for ''[[Robin Hood: Prince of Thieves]]''\n\n===Production and engineering===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Engineered Album, Non-Classical|Best Engineered Album, Non-Classical]]\n**[[Al Schmitt]], Armin Steiner, David Reitzas & Woody Woodruff (engineers) for ''[[Unforgettable... with Love]]'' performed by [[Natalie Cole]] with [[Nat King Cole]]\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Engineered Album, Classical|Best Classical Engineered Album]]\n**Gregor Zielinsky (engineer), [[Leonard Bernstein]] (conductor) & the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] for ''Bernstein: Candide  ''\n*[[Grammy Award for Producer of the Year, Non-Classical|Producer of the Year, (Non Classical)]]\n**[[David Foster]]\n*[[Grammy Award for Producer of the Year, Classical|Classical Producer of the Year]]\n**[[James Mallinson]]\n\n===R&B===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Female R&B Vocal Performance|Best R&B Vocal Performance, Female]]\n**[[Lisa Fischer]] for \"[[How Can I Ease the Pain]]\"\n**[[Patti LaBelle]] for \"[[Burnin' (Patti LaBelle album)#Track listing|Burnin']]\"\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Male R&B Vocal Performance|Best R&B Vocal Performance, Male]]\n**[[Luther Vandross]] for ''[[Power of Love (Luther Vandross album)|Power of Love]]''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best R&B Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocals|Best R&B Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal]]\n**[[Boyz II Men]] for \"[[Cooleyhighharmony]]\"\n*[[Grammy Award for Best R&B Song|Best Rhythm & Blues Song]]\n**[[Marcus Miller]], [[Luther Vandross]] & Teddy Vann (songwriters) for \"[[Power of Love/Love Power]]\" performed by Luther Vandross\n\n===Rap===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Rap Solo Performance|Best Rap Solo Performance]]\n**[[LL Cool J]] for \"[[Mama Said Knock You Out (song)|Mama Said Knock You Out]]\"\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Rap Performance by a Duo or Group|Best Rap Performance by a Duo or Group]]\n**[[DJ Jazzy Jeff & The Fresh Prince]] for \"[[Summertime (DJ Jazzy Jeff & The Fresh Prince song)|Summertime]]\"\n\n===Reggae===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Reggae Album|Best Reggae Album]]\n**[[Shabba Ranks]] for ''[[As Raw as Ever]]''\n\n===Rock===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Rock Vocal Performance, Solo|Best Rock Vocal Performance, Solo]]\n**[[Bonnie Raitt]] for ''[[Luck of the Draw (album)|Luck of the Draw]]''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal|Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal]]\n**[[Bonnie Raitt]] & [[Delbert McClinton]] for ''Good Man, Good Woman''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Rock Instrumental Performance|Best Rock Instrumental Performance]]\n**[[Eric Johnson (guitarist, born 1954)|Eric Johnson]] for \"[[Cliffs of Dover (song)|Cliffs of Dover]]\"\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Hard Rock Performance|Best Hard Rock Performance with Vocal]]\n**[[Van Halen]] for \"[[For Unlawful Carnal Knowledge]]\"  \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Metal Performance|Best Metal Performance with Vocal]]\n**[[Metallica]] for ''[[Metallica (album)|Metallica]]''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Rock Song|Best Rock Song]]\n**[[Sting (musician)|Sting]] (songwriter) for \"[[The Soul Cages#Track listing|The Soul Cages]]\"\n\n===Spoken===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Spoken Word Album|Best Spoken Word or Non-musical Album]]\n**[[Ken Burns]] for ''[[The Civil War (TV series)|The Civil War]]''\n\n===Traditional pop===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Traditional Pop Vocal Album|Best Traditional Pop Performance]]\n**[[Natalie Cole]] for ''[[Unforgettable... with Love]]''\n\n===World===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best World Music Album|Best World Music Album]]\n**[[Mickey Hart]] for ''[[Planet Drum (album)|Planet Drum]]''\n\n==Special merit awards==\n\n===[[MusiCares Person of the Year]]===\n*[[Bonnie Raitt]]\n\n===[[Grammy Legend Award]]===\n*[[Barbra Streisand]]\n\n==Trivia==\n*[[Lisa Fischer]] and [[Patti LaBelle]] tied in the category of [[Best Female R&B Vocal Performance]], therefore both won awards.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Grammy Award years}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grammy Awards 034}}\n[[Category:Grammy Awards ceremonies| 034]]\n[[Category:1992 in New York City]]\n[[Category:1992 music awards]]\n[[Category:Radio City Music Hall]]\n[[Category:1992 in American music]]\n[[Category:1992 awards in the United States|Grammy]]\n[[Category:February 1992 events in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=May 2011}}\n{{Infobox award\n| name     = 34th Annual Grammy Awards\n| image    = \n| caption  = \n| date     = February 25, 1992\n| location = [[Radio City Music Hall]], [[New York City]]\n| host     = [[Whoopi Goldberg]]\n| network  = CBS\n| previous = [[33rd Annual Grammy Awards|33rd]]\n| main     = [[Grammy&nbsp;Award]]s\n| next     = [[35th Annual Grammy Awards|35th]]\n}}\nThe '''34th Annual Grammy Awards''' were held on February 25, 1992<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/02/26/arts/cole-s-unforgettable-sweeps-the-grammys.html?src=pm|title=Cole's 'Unforgettable' Sweeps the Grammys|author=Pareles, Jon|date=26 February 1992|work=The New York Times|accessdate=26 September 2012}}</ref>, recognizing accomplishments by musicians from the previous year (1991). [[Natalie Cole]] won the most awards (three), including [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ILJRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=SW4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=3240,6416393&dq=grammy&hl=en|title=Natalie Cole emotional favorite at Grammys|author=Campbell, Mary|date=26 February 1992|publisher=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|accessdate=1 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=&title=&year=1991&genre=All|title=1991 Grammy Award Winners|publisher=Grammy.com|accessdate=1 May 2011}}</ref> [[Paul Simon (musician)|Paul Simon]] opened the show.\n\n==Award winners==\n*[[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]]\n**[[David Foster]] (producer) for \"[[Unforgettable (Nat King Cole song)|Unforgettable]]\" performed by [[Natalie Cole]] with [[Nat King Cole]]\n*[[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]]\n**[[Rufus (band)|Andr\u00e9 Fischer]], [[David Foster]] & [[Tommy LiPuma]] (producers) for ''[[Unforgettable... with Love]]'' performed by [[Natalie Cole]]\n*[[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]]\n**[[Irving Gordon]] (songwriter) for \"[[Unforgettable (Nat King Cole song)|Unforgettable]]\" performed by [[Natalie Cole]] with [[Nat King Cole]]\n*[[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]]\n**[[Marc Cohn]]\n\n===Alternative===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Alternative Music Album|Best Alternative Music Album]]\n**[[R.E.M.]] for ''[[Out of Time (album)|Out of Time]]''\n\n===Blues===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Traditional Blues Album|Best Traditional Blues Album]]\n**[[B.B. King]] for ''[[Live at the Apollo (B. B. King album)|Live at the Apollo]]'' \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Blues Album|Best Contemporary Blues Album]]\n**[[Buddy Guy]] for ''[[Damn Right, I've Got the Blues]]''\n\n===Children's===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Album for Children|Best Album for Children]]\n**Clifford \"Barney\" Robertson (producer) for ''A Capella Kids'' performed by The Maranatha! Kids\n\n===Classical===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Orchestral Performance|Best Orchestral Performance]]\n**[[Daniel Barenboim]] (conductor) & the [[Chicago Symphony Orchestra]] for ''[[John Corigliano|Corigliano]]: Symphony No. 1''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Classical Vocal Performance|Best Classical Vocal Soloist]]\n**[[Dawn Upshaw]] for ''The Girl With Orange Lips ([[Manuel de Falla|Falla]], [[Maurice Ravel|Ravel]], etc.)''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Opera Recording|Best Opera Recording]]\n**Cord Garben (producer), [[James Levine]] (conductor), [[Hildegard Behrens]], [[Reiner Goldberg]], [[Matti Salminen]], [[Hanna Schwarz]], [[Cheryl Studer]], [[Bernd Weikl]], [[Ekkehard Wlaschiha]], & the [[Metropolitan Opera Orchestra]] for ''[[Richard Wagner|Wagner]]: G\u00f6tterd\u00e4mmerung''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Choral Performance|Best Performance of a Choral Work]]\n**[[Georg Solti]] (conductor), [[Margaret Hillis]] (choir director) & the [[Chicago Symphony Orchestra|Chicago Symphony Orchestra & Chorus]] for ''[[Johann Sebastian Bach|Bach]]: Mass in B Minor''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Instrumental Soloist(s) Performance (with orchestra)|Best Instrumental Soloist With Orchestra]]\n**[[Leonard Slatkin]] (conductor), [[John Browning (pianist)|John Browning]] & the [[Saint Louis Symphony Orchestra]] for ''[[Samuel Barber|Barber]]: Piano Concerto''  \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Instrumental Soloist Performance (without orchestra)|Best Classical Performance Instrumental Solo Without Orchestra]]\n**[[Alicia de Larrocha]] for ''[[Enrique Granados|Granados]]: Goyescas; Allegro de Concierto; Danza Lenta''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Chamber Music Performance|Best Chamber Music Performance]]\n**[[Emanuel Ax]], [[Jaime Laredo]], [[Yo-Yo Ma]] & [[Isaac Stern]] for ''[[Johannes Brahms|Brahms]]: Piano Quartets (Opp. 25 and 26)''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Classical Contemporary Composition|Best Contemporary Composition]]\n**[[John Corigliano]] (composer), [[Daniel Barenboim]] (conductor) & the [[Chicago Symphony Orchestra]] for ''Corigliano: Symphony No. 1''  \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Classical Album|Best Classical Album]]\n**[[Hans Weber]] (producer), [[Leonard Bernstein]] (conductor), [[June Anderson]], [[Nicolai Gedda]], [[Adolph Green]], [[Jerry Hadley]], [[Della Jones]], [[Christa Ludwig]], [[Kurt Ollmann]] & the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] for ''Bernstein: Candide''\n\n===Comedy===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Comedy Album|Best Comedy Album]]\n**[[Peter Schickele]] for ''P.D.Q. Bach: [[WTWP Classical Talkity-Talk Radio]]''\n\n===Composing and arranging===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Instrumental Composition|Best Instrumental Composition]]\n**[[Elton John]] (composer) for \"Basque\" performed by [[James Galway]]        \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media|Best Song Written Specifically for a Motion Picture or Television]]\n**[[Bryan Adams]], [[Michael Kamen]] & [[Robert Lange|Robert John \"Mutt\" Lange]] (songwriters) for \"[[(Everything I Do) I Do It for You]]\" performed by Bryan Adams  \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Score Soundtrack Album for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media|Best Instrumental Composition Written for a Motion Picture or for Television]]\n**[[John Barry (composer)|John Barry]] (composer) for ''[[Dances With Wolves]]''  \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Instrumental Arrangement|Best Arrangement on an Instrumental]]\n**[[Dave Grusin]] (arranger) for \"[[The Gershwin Connection#Track listing|Medley: Bess You Is My Woman/I Loves You Porgy]]\"\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocalist(s)|Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocal(s)]]\n**[[Johnny Mandel]] (arranger) for \"[[Unforgettable (Nat King Cole song)|Unforgettable]]\" performed by [[Natalie Cole]] with [[Nat King Cole]]\n\n===Country===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Female Country Vocal Performance|Best Country Vocal Performance, Female]]\n**[[Mary Chapin Carpenter]] for \"[[Down at the Twist and Shout]]\"\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Male Country Vocal Performance|Best Country Vocal Performance, Male]]\n**[[Garth Brooks]] for ''[[Ropin' the Wind]]''  \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Country Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal|Best Country Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal]]\n**[[The Judds]] for \"[[Love Can Build a Bridge]]\"\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Country Collaboration with Vocals|Best Country Vocal Collaboration]]\n**[[Vince Gill]], [[Ricky Skaggs]] & [[Steve Wariner]] for \"[[Restless (Carl Perkins song)|Restless]]\"\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Country Instrumental Performance|Best Country Instrumental Performance]]\n**[[Mark O'Connor]] for ''[[The New Nashville Cats]]''  \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Country Song|Best Country Song]]\n**[[John Barlow Jarvis|John Jarvis]], [[Naomi Judd]] & [[Paul Overstreet]] (songwriters) for \"[[Love Can Build a Bridge]]\" performed by [[The Judds]]  \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Bluegrass Album|Best Bluegrass Album]]\n**[[Carl Jackson]] & John Starling for ''Spring Training''\n\n===Folk===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Traditional Folk Album|Best Traditional Folk Album]]\n**[[Ken Burns]] & [[John Colby (musician)|John Colby]] (producers) for ''[[The Civil War (TV series)#Soundtrack|The Civil War - Original Soundtrack]]'' performed by various artists  \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Folk Album|Best Contemporary Folk Album]]\n**[[John Prine]] for ''[[The Missing Years (album)|The Missing Years]]''\n\n===Gospel===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Pop/Contemporary Gospel Album|Best Pop Gospel Album]]\n**[[Steven Curtis Chapman]] for ''For the Sake of the Call''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Rock Gospel Album|Best Rock/Contemporary Gospel Album]]\n**[[Russ Taff]] for ''Under Their Influence''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Traditional Soul Gospel Album|Best Traditional Soul Gospel Album]]\n**[[Mighty Clouds of Joy]] for ''Pray For Me''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Soul Gospel Album|Best Contemporary Soul Gospel Album]]\n**[[BeBe Winans]] & [[CeCe Winans]] for ''Different Lifestyles'' \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Southern, Country or Bluegrass Gospel Album|Best Southern Gospel Album]]\n**The [[Gaither Vocal Band]] for ''Homecoming'' \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Gospel Choir or Chorus Album|Best Gospel Album by Choir or Chorus]]\n**[[Gary Hines]] (choir director) for ''The Evolution of Gospel'' performed by The [[Sounds of Blackness]]\n\n===Historical===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Historical Album|Best Historical Album]]\n**Steven Lasker & Andy McKaie (producers) for [[Billie Holiday]] - ''The Complete Decca Recordings''\n\n===Jazz===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Jazz Instrumental Solo|Best Jazz Instrumental Solo]]\n**[[Stan Getz]] for \"I Remember You\"\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Jazz Instrumental Album, Individual or Group|Best Jazz Instrumental Performance, Group]]\n**The [[Oscar Peterson Trio]] for ''[[Saturday Night at the Blue Note]]''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Large Jazz Ensemble Album|Best Large Jazz Ensemble Performance]]\n**[[Dizzy Gillespie]] for ''[[Live at the Royal Festival Hall (Dizzy Gillespie album)|Live at the Royal Festival Hall]]''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Jazz Vocal Album|Best Jazz Vocal Performance]]\n**[[Take 6]] for ''[[He Is Christmas]]''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Jazz Album|Best Contemporary Jazz Performance]]\n**[[The Manhattan Transfer]] for \"[[The Offbeat of Avenues|Sassy]]\"\n\n===Latin===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop Album|Best Latin Pop Album]]\n**[[Vikki Carr]] for ''[[Cosas del Amor (Vikki Carr album)|Cosas del Amor]] '' \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Traditional Tropical Latin Album|Best Tropical Latin Album]]\n**[[Juan Luis Guerra]] for ''[[Bachata Rosa]]''  \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Mexican/Mexican-American Album|Best Mexican-American Album]]\n**[[Little Joe (singer)|Little Joe]] for ''[[16 de Septiembre]]''\n\n===Musical show===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Musical Show Album|Best Musical Show Album]]\n**[[Cy Coleman]] (producer and composer), [[Mike Berniker]] (producer), [[Adolph Green]], [[Betty Comden]] (lyricists) & the original Broadway cast for ''[[The Will Rogers Follies]]''\n\n===Music video===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Short Form Music Video|Best Music Video, Short Form]]\n**[[Tarsem]] (video director) & [[R.E.M.]] for \"[[Losing My Religion]]\"\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Long Form Music Video|Best Music Video, Long Form]]\n**[[Anthony Eaton]] (video producer), [[David Mallet (director)|David Mallet]], Mark \"Aldo\" Miceli (video directors) & [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] for ''Madonna:  [[Blond Ambition World Tour Live]]''\n\n===New Age===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best New Age Album|Best New Age Album]]\n**[[Chip Davis]] for ''[[Fresh Aire 7]]''\n\n===Packaging and notes===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Recording Package|Best Album Package]]\n**Vartan (art director) for ''Billie Holiday - The Complete Decca Recordings''  performed by [[Billie Holiday]] \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Album Notes|Best Album Notes]]\n**Alan M. Leeds, Cliff White, Harry Weinger, [[James Brown (musician)|James Brown]] & [[Nelson George]] (notes writers) for ''[[Star Time]]'' performed by James Brown\n\n===Polka===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Polka Album|Best Polka Album]]\n**[[Jimmy Sturr]] for ''[[Live at Gilley's!]]''\n\n===Pop===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Female Pop Vocal Performance|Best Pop Vocal Performance, Female]]\n**[[Bonnie Raitt]] for \"[[Something to Talk About (Bonnie Raitt song)|Something to Talk About]]\"\n\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Male Pop Vocal Performance|Best Pop Vocal Performance, Male]]\n**[[Michael Bolton]] for \"[[When a Man Loves a Woman (song)|When a Man Loves a Woman]]\"\n\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Pop Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal|Best Pop Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal]]\n**[[R.E.M.]] for \"[[Losing My Religion]]\"\n\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Pop Instrumental Performance|Best Pop Instrumental Performance]]\n**[[Michael Kamen]] for ''[[Robin Hood: Prince of Thieves]]''\n\n===Production and engineering===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Engineered Album, Non-Classical|Best Engineered Album, Non-Classical]]\n**[[Al Schmitt]], Armin Steiner, David Reitzas & Woody Woodruff (engineers) for ''[[Unforgettable... with Love]]'' performed by [[Natalie Cole]] with [[Nat King Cole]]\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Engineered Album, Classical|Best Classical Engineered Album]]\n**Gregor Zielinsky (engineer), [[Leonard Bernstein]] (conductor) & the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] for ''Bernstein: Candide  ''\n*[[Grammy Award for Producer of the Year, Non-Classical|Producer of the Year, (Non Classical)]]\n**[[David Foster]]\n*[[Grammy Award for Producer of the Year, Classical|Classical Producer of the Year]]\n**[[James Mallinson]]\n\n===R&B===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Female R&B Vocal Performance|Best R&B Vocal Performance, Female]]\n**[[Lisa Fischer]] for \"[[How Can I Ease the Pain]]\"\n**[[Patti LaBelle]] for \"[[Burnin' (Patti LaBelle album)#Track listing|Burnin']]\"\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Male R&B Vocal Performance|Best R&B Vocal Performance, Male]]\n**[[Luther Vandross]] for ''[[Power of Love (Luther Vandross album)|Power of Love]]''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best R&B Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocals|Best R&B Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal]]\n**[[Boyz II Men]] for \"[[Cooleyhighharmony]]\"\n*[[Grammy Award for Best R&B Song|Best Rhythm & Blues Song]]\n**[[Marcus Miller]], [[Luther Vandross]] & Teddy Vann (songwriters) for \"[[Power of Love/Love Power]]\" performed by Luther Vandross\n\n===Rap===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Rap Solo Performance|Best Rap Solo Performance]]\n**[[LL Cool J]] for \"[[Mama Said Knock You Out (song)|Mama Said Knock You Out]]\"\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Rap Performance by a Duo or Group|Best Rap Performance by a Duo or Group]]\n**[[DJ Jazzy Jeff & The Fresh Prince]] for \"[[Summertime (DJ Jazzy Jeff & The Fresh Prince song)|Summertime]]\"\n\n===Reggae===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Reggae Album|Best Reggae Album]]\n**[[Shabba Ranks]] for ''[[As Raw as Ever]]''\n\n===Rock===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Rock Vocal Performance, Solo|Best Rock Vocal Performance, Solo]]\n**[[Bonnie Raitt]] for ''[[Luck of the Draw (album)|Luck of the Draw]]''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal|Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal]]\n**[[Bonnie Raitt]] & [[Delbert McClinton]] for ''Good Man, Good Woman''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Rock Instrumental Performance|Best Rock Instrumental Performance]]\n**[[Eric Johnson (guitarist, born 1954)|Eric Johnson]] for \"[[Cliffs of Dover (song)|Cliffs of Dover]]\"\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Hard Rock Performance|Best Hard Rock Performance with Vocal]]\n**[[Van Halen]] for \"[[For Unlawful Carnal Knowledge]]\"  \n*[[Grammy Award for Best Metal Performance|Best Metal Performance with Vocal]]\n**[[Metallica]] for ''[[Metallica (album)|Metallica]]''\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Rock Song|Best Rock Song]]\n**[[Sting (musician)|Sting]] (songwriter) for \"[[The Soul Cages#Track listing|The Soul Cages]]\"\n\n===Spoken===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Spoken Word Album|Best Spoken Word or Non-musical Album]]\n**[[Ken Burns]] for ''[[The Civil War (TV series)|The Civil War]]''\n\n===Traditional pop===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best Traditional Pop Vocal Album|Best Traditional Pop Performance]]\n**[[Natalie Cole]] for ''[[Unforgettable... with Love]]''\n\n===World===\n*[[Grammy Award for Best World Music Album|Best World Music Album]]\n**[[Mickey Hart]] for ''[[Planet Drum (album)|Planet Drum]]''\n\n==Special merit awards==\n\n===[[MusiCares Person of the Year]]===\n*[[Bonnie Raitt]]\n\n===[[Grammy Legend Award]]===\n*[[Barbra Streisand]]\n\n==Trivia==\n*[[Lisa Fischer]] and [[Patti LaBelle]] tied in the category of [[Best Female R&B Vocal Performance]], therefore both won awards.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Grammy Award years}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grammy Awards 034}}\n[[Category:Grammy Awards ceremonies| 034]]\n[[Category:1992 in New York City]]\n[[Category:1992 music awards]]\n[[Category:Radio City Music Hall]]\n[[Category:1992 in American music]]\n[[Category:1992 awards in the United States|Grammy]]\n[[Category:February 1992 events in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-Gary Hines", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/34th_Annual_Grammy_Awards"}
{"title_page": "Suniel Shetty filmography", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{short description|Filmography of Indian actor Suniel Shetty}}\n[[File:Suniel Shetty at Tata Sky's Health And Fitness launch.jpg|thumb|Shetty in 2015]]\n[[Suniel Shetty]] is an Indian actor and producer known for his work in [[Bollywood]], and has also appeared in [[Tamil language|Tamil]], [[Marathi language|Marathi]], [[Kannada]], [[Malayalam]] and English language films.\n\n==Films==\n===Actor===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Year !! Film !! Role !! Other notes \n|-\n| 1992 || ''[[Balwaan]]'' || Arjun Singh || \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1993 || ''[[Waqt Hamara Hai]]'' || Sunil Chaudhary ||\n|-\n|''[[Pehchaan (1993 film)|Pehchaan]]'' || Kunal Verma ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | 1994 || ''[[Dilwale (1994 film)|Dilwale]]'' || Vikram Singh || Nominated\u2014[[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actor]]\n\n|-\n|''[[Anth]]'' || Vijay Saxena ||\n|-\n|''[[Mohra]]'' || Vishal Agnihotri ||\n|-\n|''[[Gopi Kishan]]'' || Gopi / Kishan || Double Role\n\n|-\n|''[[Hum Hain Bemisaal]]'' || Michael ||\n\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 1995 || ''[[Surakshaa (1995 film)|Surakshaa]]'' || Raja ||\n|-\n| ''Raghuveer (1995 film) |Raghuveer'' || Raghuveer ||\n|-\n|''[[Gaddaar (1995 film)|Gaddaar]]'' || Sunny ||\n|-\n|''[[Takkar (1995 film)|Takkar]]'' || Ravi Malhotra ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" | 1996 || ''[[Ek Tha Raja]]'' || Jay ||\n|-\n|''[[Vishwasghaat]]'' || Avinash ||\n|-\n|''[[Krishna (1996 Hindi film)|Krishna]]'' || Krishna / Sunil ||\n|-\n|''[[Shastra (1996 film)|Shastra]]'' || Vijay ||\n|-\n|''[[Sapoot]]'' || Raj Singhania ||\n|-\n|''[[Rakshak]]'' || Raj Sinha ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" | 1997 || ''[[Border (1997 film)|Border]]'' || Bhairav Singh || Nominated\u2014Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actor\n\n|-\n|''[[Prithvi (1997 film)|Prithvi]]'' || Prithvi ||\n|-\n|''[[Jud