{"title_page": "2009 Nova Scotia general election", "text_new": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2009 Nova Scotia general election\n| country            = Nova Scotia\n| type               = parliamentary\n| party_colour       = no\n| party_name         = no\n| previous_election  = 2006 Nova Scotia general election\n| previous_year      = 2006\n| previous_mps       = 60th General Assembly of Nova Scotia\n| election_date      = June 9, 2009\n| elected_mps        = [[61st General Assembly of Nova Scotia|members]]\n| next_election      = 2013 Nova Scotia general election\n| next_year          = 2013\n| next_mps           = 62nd General Assembly of Nova Scotia\n| seats_for_election = 52 seats of the [[Nova Scotia House of Assembly]] <br /> 27 seats were needed for a majority\n| image1             = [[Image:Darrell Dexter 2.jpg|150x150px]]\n| colour1            = {{Canadian party colour|NS|NDP|nohash}}\n| leader1            = [[Darrell Dexter]]\n| leader_since1  =  [[Nova Scotia New Democratic Party leadership elections#2002 leadership convention|June 2, 2002]]\n| party1             = {{Canadian party colour|NS|NDP|name}}\n| leaders_seat1      = [[Cole Harbour (electoral district)|Cole Harbour]]\n| last_election1     = 20 seats, 34.63%\n| seats1             = 31\n| seat_change1       = {{increase}}11\n| popular_vote1      = 186,556\n| percentage1        = 45.24%\n| swing1             = {{increase}}10.61%\n| image2             = [[Image:Stephen_McNeil_color-balanced.jpg|150x150px]]\n| colour2            = {{Canadian party colour|NS|Liberal|nohash}}\n| leader2            = [[Stephen McNeil]]\n| leader_since2  = [[2007 Nova Scotia Liberal Party leadership election|April 28, 2007]]\n| party2             = {{Canadian party colour|NS|Liberal|name}}\n| leaders_seat2      = [[Annapolis (provincial electoral district)|Annapolis]]\n| last_election2     = 9 seats, 23.44%\n| seats2             = 11\n| seat_change2       = {{increase}}2\n| popular_vote2      = 112,160\n| percentage2        = 27.20%\n| swing2             = {{increase}}3.76%\n| image3             = [[File:Rodney MacDonald cropped.png|150x150px]]\n| colour3            = {{Canadian party colour|NS|PC|nohash}}\n| leader3            = [[Rodney MacDonald]]\n| leader_since3      = [[2006 Progressive Conservative Association of Nova Scotia leadership election|February 11, 2006]]\n| party3             = {{Canadian party colour|NS|PC|name}}\n| leaders_seat3      = [[Inverness (provincial electoral district)|Inverness]]\n| last_election3     = 23 seats, 39.57%\n| seats3             = 10\n| seat_change3       = {{decrease}}13\n| popular_vote3      = 101,203\n| percentage3        = 24.54%\n| swing3             = {{decrease}}15.03%\n| map_image          = Nova_Scotia_Election_2009_-_Results_by_Riding.svg\n| map_size           = 400px\n| map_caption        = Popular vote by riding. As this is an FPTP election, seat totals are not determined by popular vote, but instead via results by each riding.\n| title              = Premier\n| before_election    = [[Rodney MacDonald]]\n| before_party       = {{Canadian party colour|NS|PC|name}}\n| after_election     = [[Darrell Dexter]]\n| posttitle          = Premier after election\n| after_party        = {{Canadian party colour|NS|NDP|name}}\n}}\nThe '''2009 Nova Scotia general election''' was held on June 9, 2009 to elect members of the [[61st General Assembly of Nova Scotia|61st House of Assembly]] of the Province of [[Nova Scotia]], [[Canada]]. The government was defeated on a [[money bill]] on May 4, and the [[Nova Scotia House of Assembly]] was dissolved by [[Lieutenant Governor of Nova Scotia|Lieutenant Governor]] [[Mayann Francis]] on May 5.<ref name=\"campaign begins\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/nova-scotia-goes-to-the-polls-june-9/article1197230/|title=Nova Scotia goes to the polls June 9|work=The Globe and Mail|date=May 5, 2009|accessdate=2015-05-27}}</ref> thereby triggering an election. The NDP won a majority government, forming government the first time in the province's history, and for the first time in an Atlantic Canadian province. The governing Progressive Conservatives were reduced to third place.\n\n==Campaign==\nThe election campaign began on May 5, 2009, after the New Democrats and Liberals voted against the Offshore Offset Revenues Expenditure Act, legislation that would have permitted the government to divert its revenues from oil and gas development in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] from debt payment, as required under current provincial law, to fund extra spending in the 2009 budget.<ref name=\"government defeated\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ready-to-vote-nova-scotia-s-minority-tory-government-falls-1.804133|title=Ready to vote? Nova Scotia's minority Tory government falls|work=CBC News|date=May 4, 2009|accessdate=2015-05-27}}</ref> As the Progressive Conservatives won only a [[minority government]] in the [[2006 Nova Scotia general election|2006 election]], at least one of the two opposition parties would have been required to vote in favour of (or abstain from voting on) the legislation for it to pass.\n\n== Timeline ==\n*June 13, 2006 - [[Rodney MacDonald]]'s [[Progressive Conservative Association of Nova Scotia|Progressive Conservatives]] are elected to a minority government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia-tories-win-minority-1.596707|title=Nova Scotia Tories win minority|publisher=CBC News|date=June 13, 2006|accessdate=2016-05-23}}</ref>\n*June 20, 2006 - Liberal leader [[Francis MacKenzie]] resigns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mackenzie-steps-down-as-liberal-leader-1.627013|title=MacKenzie steps down as Liberal leader|publisher=CBC News|date=June 20, 2006|accessdate=2016-05-23}}</ref>\n*February 20, 2007 - [[Cumberland North]] MLA [[Ernie Fage]] is suspended from the Progressive Conservative caucus after Halifax Police charge him with failing to remain at the scene of an accident, following an incident in November 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/fage-charged-suspended-from-tory-caucus-1.650815|title=Fage charged, suspended from Tory caucus|publisher=CBC News|date=February 20, 2007|accessdate=2016-05-23}}</ref>\n*March 1, 2007 - NDP MLA [[Kevin Deveaux]] resigns his seat of [[Cole Harbour-Eastern Passage]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ndp-s-deveaux-quits-politics-for-un-post-1.644999|title=NDP's Deveaux quits politics for UN post|publisher=CBC News|date=January 25, 2007|accessdate=2016-05-23}}</ref>\n*April 28, 2007 - [[Stephen McNeil]] is elected leader of the [[Nova Scotia Liberal Party]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/mcneil-new-n-s-liberal-leader-1.689242|title=McNeil new N.S. Liberal leader|publisher=CBC News|date=April 28, 2007|accessdate=2016-05-23}}</ref>\n*October 2, 2007 - [[Becky Kent]] of the NDP is elected in the [[2007 Cole Harbour-Eastern Passage provincial by-election|Cole Harbour-Eastern Passage byelection]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ndp-holds-seat-in-halifax-area-byelection-1.642885|title=NDP holds seat in Halifax-area byelection|publisher=CBC News|date=October 2, 2007|accessdate=2016-05-23}}</ref>\n*December 18, 2007 - Fage is convicted of leaving the scene of an accident, and is expelled from the Progressive Conservative caucus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/fage-tossed-from-n-s-caucus-after-conviction-1.659507|title=Fage tossed from N.S. caucus after conviction|publisher=CBC News|date=December 18, 2007|accessdate=2016-05-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/n-s-politician-convicted-booted-from-caucus-1.268036|title=N.S. politician convicted, booted from caucus|publisher=CTV News|date=December 18, 2007|accessdate=2016-05-23}}</ref>\n*March 2, 2009 - [[Lunenburg (provincial electoral district)|Lunenburg]] MLA and Finance Minister [[Michael Baker (politician)|Michael Baker]] dies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-s-finance-minister-dies-of-cancer-1.808049|title=Nova Scotia's finance minister dies of cancer|publisher=CBC News|date=March 3, 2009|accessdate=2016-05-23}}</ref>\n*May 4, 2009 - Government is defeated on a budget bill (Bill 240 - ''Offshore Offset Revenues Expenditure Act'' (amendments to ''Provincial finance Act'')).<ref name=\"government defeated\"/>\n*May 5, 2009 - Legislature is officially dissolved and election is called for June 9, 2009.<ref name=\"campaign begins\"/>\n\n{| style=\"width:65%; text-align:center;\"\n|+ \u2193\n|- style=\"color:white;\"\n| style=\"background:#F4A460; width:59.62%;\" | '''31'''\n| style=\"background:#F08080; width:21.15%;\" | '''11'''\n| style=\"background:#9999FF; width:19.23%;\" | '''10'''\n|-\n| <span style=\"color:#F4A460;\">'''New Democratic'''</span>\n| <span style=\"color:#F08080;\">'''Liberal'''</span>\n| <span style=\"color:#9999FF;\">'''Progressive Conservative'''</span>\n|}\n\n===Results by party===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"2\"|Party\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Party leader\n!rowspan=\"2\"|# of<br />candidates\n!colspan=\"4\"|Seats\n!colspan=\"3\"|Popular vote\n|-\n![[2006 Nova Scotia general election|2006]]\n!<span style=\"font-size: 75%;\">[[Dissolution of parliament|Dissolution]]</span>\n!Elected\n!% Change\n!#\n!%\n!Change\n{{Canadian party colour|NS|NDP|row}}\n|[[New Democratic Party of Nova Scotia|New Democratic]]\n|[[Darrell Dexter]]\n|align=\"right\"|52\n|align=\"right\"|20\n|align=\"right\"|20\n|align=\"right\"|'''31'''\n|align=\"right\"|+55.0%\n|align=\"right\"|186,556\n|align=\"right\"|45.24%\n|align=\"right\"|+10.61%\n{{Canadian party colour|NS|Liberal|row}}\n|[[Liberal Party of Nova Scotia|Liberal]]\n|[[Stephen McNeil]]\n|align=\"right\"|52\n|align=\"right\"|9\n|align=\"right\"|9\n|align=\"right\"|'''11'''\n|align=\"right\"|+22.2%\n|align=\"right\"|112,160\n|align=\"right