{"title_page": "2006 Nova Scotia general election", "text_new": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2006 Nova Scotia general election\n| country            = Nova Scotia\n| type               = parliamentary\n| party_colour       = no\n| party_name         = no\n| previous_election  = 2003 Nova Scotia general election\n| previous_year      = 2003\n| previous_mps       = 59th General Assembly of Nova Scotia\n| election_date      = June 13, 2006\n| elected_mps        = [[60th General Assembly of Nova Scotia|members]]\n| next_election      = 2009 Nova Scotia general election\n| next_year          = 2009\n| next_mps           = 61st General Assembly of Nova Scotia\n| seats_for_election = 52 seats of the [[Nova Scotia House of Assembly]]\n| majority_seats     = 27\n| image1             = [[File:Rodney MacDonald cropped.png|150x150px]]\n| colour1            = {{Canadian party colour|NS|PC|nohash}}\n| leader1            = [[Rodney MacDonald]]\n| leader_since1      = [[2006 Progressive Conservative Association of Nova Scotia leadership election|February 11, 2006]]\n| party1             = {{Canadian party colour|NS|PC|name}}\n| leaders_seat1      = [[Inverness (provincial electoral district)|Inverness]]\n| last_election1     = 25 seats, 36.32%\n| seats1             = 23\n| seat_change1       = {{decrease}}2\n| popular_vote1      = 160,119\n| percentage1        = 39.57%\n| swing1             = {{increase}}3.33%\n| image2             = [[Image:Darrell Dexter 2.jpg|150x150px]]\n| colour2            = {{Canadian party colour|NS|NDP|nohash}}\n| leader2            = [[Darrell Dexter]]\n| leader_since2      = [[Nova Scotia New Democratic Party leadership elections#2002 leadership convention|June 2, 2002]]\n| party2             = {{Canadian party colour|NS|NDP|name}}\n| leaders_seat2      = [[Cole Harbour (electoral district)|Cole Harbour]]\n| last_election2     = 15 seats, 31.00%\n| seats2             = 20\n| seat_change2       = {{increase}}5\n| popular_vote2      = 140,128\n| percentage2        = 34.63%\n| swing2             = {{increase}}3.52%\n| image3             = \n<div style=\"width:115px;\"><span style=\"line-height:150px; vertical-align:center; text-align:center; color:{{Canadian party colour|NS|Liberal}}; font-size:38px;\"> '''LIB''' </span></div>\n| colour3            = {{Canadian party colour|NS|Liberal|nohash}}\n| leader3            = [[Francis MacKenzie]]\n| leader_since3      = [[Nova Scotia Liberal Party leadership elections#2004 leadership convention|October 23, 2004]]\n| party3             = {{Canadian party colour|NS|Liberal|name}}\n| leaders_seat3      = ''Ran in [[Bedford (electoral district)|Bedford]] (lost)''\n| last_election3     = 12 seats, 31.47%\n| seats3             = 9\n| seat_change3       = {{decrease}}3\n| popular_vote3      = 94,872\n| percentage3        = 23.44%\n| swing3             = {{decrease}}7.99%\n| map_image          = Nova_Scotia_Election_2006_-_Results_by_Riding.svg\n| map_size           = 400px\n| map_caption        = Popular vote by riding. As this is an FPTP election, seat totals are not determined by popular vote, but instead via results by each riding.\n| title              = Premier\n| before_election    = [[Rodney MacDonald]]\n| before_party       = {{Canadian party colour|NS|PC|name}}\n| after_election     = [[Rodney MacDonald]]\n| posttitle         = Premier after election\n| after_party        = {{Canadian party colour|NS|PC|name}}\n}}\nThe '''2006 Nova Scotia general election''' was held on June 13, 2006 to elect members of the [[60th General Assembly of Nova Scotia|60th House of Assembly]] of the Province of [[Nova Scotia]], [[Canada]].\n\n[[Premier of Nova Scotia|Premier]] [[Rodney MacDonald]], who led a [[Progressive Conservative Party of Nova Scotia|Progressive Conservative]] [[minority government]] in the legislature, called for the election on May 13, 2006, hoping for a [[majority government]] to better advance his agenda and a clear mandate for himself as he had not yet fought an election as leader.\n\nUltimately, MacDonald was returned to power leading another, slightly smaller, minority government against a strengthened [[Nova Scotia New Democratic Party|New Democratic Party]] sitting as the [[Official Opposition]] and a weakened [[Liberal Party of Nova Scotia|Liberal Party]]. Liberal leader [[Francis MacKenzie]] was defeated in his riding of Bedford.\n\n== Timeline ==\n*September 29, 2005 - Premier [[John Hamm]], leader of the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Nova Scotia|Progressive Conservative]] [[minority government]], announces his intent to resign as soon as the party chooses a new leader.\n*February 11, 2006 - [[Rodney MacDonald]] is elected to replace Hamm as leader.\n*February 24, 2006 - MacDonald becomes Premier and his [[Executive Council of Nova Scotia|cabinet]] is sworn in.\n*May 9, 2006 - MacDonald's government introduces an \"election-style\" budget in the legislature.\n*May 13, 2006 - Premier [[Rodney MacDonald]] calls a general election for June 13, 2006.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-vote-called-for-june-13-1.609637 | work=CBC News | title=Nova Scotia vote called for June 13 | date=May 13, 2006}}</ref>\n\n==Campaign==\nMacKenzie was an outspoken critic of the governing Tories and accused them of living in a \"fantasy world\" due to their promise to cut taxes and increase spending in the 2006-07 budget.<ref name=\"MacKenzie\"/>\n\nNo single issue dominated the election campaign, with all parties offering up various promises for university students to seniors.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/nsvotes2006/ Tories win minority, lose two seats] CBC News, June 14, 2006</ref>\n\n==Opinion polling==\nA March 2006 poll by Corporate Research Associates asked voters who they would prefer as premier, 36 per cent of respondents picked Premier Rodney MacDonald, compared to 23 per cent for Darrell Dexter and 16 per cent for Francis MacKenzie. The same poll showed the Progressive Conservatives in the lead with 36 percent of voters compared to 29 percent for the New Democrats and 27 percent for the Liberals.<ref name=\"MacKenzie\">[http://www.cbc.ca/nsvotes2006/parties/LIBmackenzie.html Parties & Leaders - Francis MacKenzie] CBC News, June 2, 2006</ref>\n\n==Results==\n\nThe Progressive Conservatives gained several points in the popular vote, but made a net loss of two seats, with losses to the NDP partially countered by the PCs doubling their representation on MacDonald's native Cape Breton Island at the expense of the Liberals. The gap between the Liberals and NDP also significantly increased, in both the popular vote and seat count; while the Liberals and NDP had previously been nearly even, the NDP gained a significant advantage on the Liberals and moved into position as the primary opposition to the governing PCs.\n\n===Results by party===\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; border-color: #444444\"\n|- bgcolor=\"CCCCCC\"\n!rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"2\"|Party\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Party leader\n!rowspan=\"2\"|# of<br />candidates\n!colspan=\"4\"|Seats\n!colspan=\"3\"|Popular vote\n|- bgcolor=\"CCCCCC\"\n|align=\"center\"|[[2003 Nova Scotia general election|2003]]\n|align=\"center\"|<span style=\"font-size: 75%;\">[[Dissolution of parliament|Dissolution]]</span>\n|align=\"center\"|'''Elected'''\n|align=\"center\"|% Change\n|align=\"center\"|#\n|align=\"center\"|%\n|align=\"center\"|Change\n{{Canadian party colour|NS|PC|row}}\n|[[Progressive Conservative Party of Nova Scotia|Progressive Conservative]]\n|[[Rodney MacDonald]]\n|align=\"right\"|52\n|align=\"right\"|25\n|align=\"right\"|25\n!align=\"right\"|23\n|align=\"right\"|-8.0%\n|align=\"right\"|160,119\n|align=\"right\"|39.57%\n|align=\"right\"|+3.33%\n{{Canadian party colour|NS|NDP|row}}\n|[[New Democratic Party of Nova Scotia|New Democratic]]\n|[[Darrell Dexter]]\n|align=\"right\"|52\n|align=\"right\"|15\n|align=\"right\"|15\n!align=\"right\"|20\n|alig